{"type":"message","id":"fa815955","parentId":"4938629a","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:12:55.668Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me compare current state vs. last known state.\n\n**Last known state (from heartbeat-state.json):**\n- Active sessions: cron:ed2d0b5d, cron:6f3323ef, cron:e7885813, telegram:group:-5163901258\n- Last report: 10:00 UTC 14 Apr\n- Blockers: Telegram gateway timeout\n\n**Current state (from sessions_list at 10:09 UTC):**\nActive sessions (status=running):\n1. cron:6f3323ef ✅ (this cron session itself - running)\n\n\n2. cron:ed2d0b5d ✅ (still running)\n3. cron:e7885813 ✅ (still running)\n4. telegram:group:-5163901258 ✅ (still running)\n5. cron:ac986a8d ✅ (new session - not in last state)\n\nThere's also a terminated Telegram direct session with 6 child subagents that ran during this period, plus a few other cron sessions that were already completed.\n\nLooking at the actual changes from the last heartbeat at 10:00, the most significant shift is that the Lead's direct session transitioned from a failed state with 6 subagents back to running, and it completed successfully at 10:08 with a comprehensive 79-endpoint test report. The cron:ac986a8d session spawned around 10:04 is also new but appears to be a short-lived automation task. I'm looking at the session details more carefully now. The parent session `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134` ran from 10:18 to 10:25 and successfully completed the full API test, so that's a real change to track since the last heartbeat.\n\nComparing the session states between the last heartbeat and now, I'm noticing the active sessions look similar on the surface—same cron jobs and group sessions—but there are new failed sub-agents and terminated sessions that weren't present before. The cron job that was running at the last check appears to have completed and started a new one, which suggests active work happening in the background.\n\nLooking at the failed sessions, I see a pattern of provider API errors across multiple sub-agents, likely stemming from an authentication issue with the `AHV-Holding-TroLy` model. The parent session completed successfully at 10:08, which is the main positive signal here, but the consistent failures across different agent types point to a deeper infrastructure problem rather than individual task failures.\n\nChecking the timestamps more carefully, the cron session that runs every 5 minutes started at 09:32 UTC, which means the 10:00 report I'm looking at might be from the first iteration rather than the second one. I'm trying to reconcile whether the 09:32 start time aligns with the pattern I'm seeing in the heartbeat timestamps.\n\nLooking at the actual changes that occurred, the Lead's direct session started and completed between the 10:00 and 10:05 cycles, which means the 10:00 state didn't capture it yet. So when I compare the session list from 10:09 against the last heartbeat at 10:00, I need to account for what was actually active at each point—the cron sessions, the telegram group session, and now the completed lead session. I'm parsing through the heartbeat report timestamp to confirm it was generated at 10:09 UTC on April 14th, which matches when the cron job ran. The direct Telegram session completed at 10:08:14 UTC, so this is the first opportunity to report on those completed changes since the last state snapshot.\n\nThe main findings are that the Lead's Telegram session with its six sub-agents successfully ran the full API test, and while a monitoring cron started around 10:04 UTC, it doesn't appear in the active list anymore—either it was very brief or got interrupted. I should verify the cron state and provide this update.","thinkingSignature":"dea4d3e02270ccd69ffbdb4601fa2ce5e30969f2f183bd2dc260103f24137112"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0xcbq17820ov_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/memory